column11: The Kaesong Industrial Complex, the hallmark of peaceful engagement between North Korea and South Korea during the previous sunshine period, was closed in February 2016 after North Korea's fourth nuclear test (BBC, The Guardian). Moon Jae-In, South Korea's new President promised to seek rapprochement with North Korea, including by re-opening Kaesong (The Diplomat, The Korea Herald). Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

According to a report from South Korea's Yonhap News Agency, the chairman of the Kaesong Industrial Complex Enterprise Association applied for permission to visit the complex to conduct preliminary inspections of South Korean-owned facilities back on February 26, but the South Korean government has yet to respond to the request. Said the chairman: "We are all set to make the trip north. Once the government gives permission, we can get up there within a day." Conducting these facilities inspections would be the first step towards reopening the complex. The association believes the government will grant such permission by the end of this month or next month and that the park will be operational again "within the year."

There is a small possibility that the increased sense of optimism and cooperation fostered by the Pyeongchang Olympics will lead to the reopening of the KIC. Since South Korea closed the KIC in response to North Korea's growing nuclear ambitions, however, it is unlikely that the KIC will reopen unless nuclear-related discussions make some serious headway in the near future.

The North Koreans are using ICBMs to leverage the South Koreans to offer financial incentives. One of these would be the industrial complex in the DMZ area. Such financial incentives would carve out an glimmer of hope during the rapid ratcheting up of sanctions by the United States (and China) on North Korea. Further "internal" negotiations for DMZ activities increases the possibility of Seoul using this industrial zone to expand Panmunjom talks in the DMZ area.

North Korea appears to have no intentions to denuclearize the country nor do they have any intent on stopping the progression of their nuclear program. The complex was closed down in 2016 after North Korea conducted its fourth nuclear test. Since the closure, North Korea has conducted two more nuclear tests. Another factor that would now make it difficult to reopen the complex would be the fact that a U.N. sanctions related review would be needed. When the complex was open South Korea firms would send the wages to a committee running the complex who would then distribute coupons or bills to the workers which was equal to 30-40 percent of the total wages. The sanctions placed on North Korea by the UN has called for closing such committees that were used to distribute the wages. Therefore, in order for the same process to be utilized if the complex were to re-open the UN would have to review their sanctions or eliminate these sanctions. http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/northkorea/2017/05/11/80/0401000000AEN20170511006000315F.html

In December 2017, an expert panel investigating the decision to close the park found that there was no evidence that North Korea had diverted wages to fund its nuclear program. The head of the panel Kim Jong-soo said, "The presidential office inserted the wage-diversion argument as major grounds, yet without concrete information, sufficient evidence and consultations with related agencies, mainly citing defector testimonies that lack objectivity and credibility. This impairs the decision’s legitimacy and could constrain our ground over a future restart of the complex, while hampering the companies’ rights to protect their assets due to the hasty pullout process."

North Korea appears to be conducting agricultural activity amid the (shuttered?) industrial facilities there. Does this activity account for the totality of what is going on there? Or is it possible that reports of activity there include attempts, successful or not, to restart these industrial facilities? If evidence were to surface that North Korea has figured out how to operate those facilities, then it would only need South Korea assistance in order to evade sanctions against its exports. That would lower probability. If North Korea can't operate these facilities alone, then there remain two hurdles instead of just the sanctions evasion hurdle. I'm not going to 100% not before Aug. 1, 2018 because it is possible that the standoff over nuclear threats might ease by then.
